<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,151,895]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,323,691,716]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick" authorityName="Meyrick" box="[665,900,692,716]" class="Insecta" family="Cosmopterigidae" genus="Scaeosopha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incantata">
<emphasis box="[665,679,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[693,799,693,716]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">incantata</emphasis>
Meyrick
</taxonomicName>
in the male genitalia, but can be separated from it by the brachia of uncus with a sclerotized triangular process at basal 1/3 and the tegumen slightly cancave on anterior margin. In 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick" authorityName="Meyrick" box="[370,609,764,788]" class="Insecta" family="Cosmopterigidae" genus="Scaeosopha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="incantata">
<emphasis box="[370,504,764,788]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">S. incantata</emphasis>
Meyrick
</taxonomicName>
, the brachia of uncus do not possess a process and the tegumen is deeply concave on anterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[472,557,799,823]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–42" captionStartId="18.[151,263,1943,1966]" captionTargetBox="[232,1344,669,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-286@18.[226,1360,637,1922]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 39–42. Male genitalia of Scaeosopha spp. 39, S. spinivalvata sp. nov., holotype, BMNH Microlep. slide no. 31023; 40, S. tuberculata sp. nov., holotype, genitalia slide no. ZZW08050; 41, S. victoriensis sp. nov., holotype, BMNH Microlep. slide no. 32349; 42, S. incantata Meyrick, BMNH Microlep. slide no. 31006." pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,151,895]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,335,836,860]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new specific epithet is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[911,1012,837,860]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">trigonius</emphasis>
= triangular, in reference to the triangular process at basal 1/3 of the uncus brachium.
</paragraph>
